From abde48704a354a8638266f5af1392f973afc9d28 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Vasu Bhatia <git@vbh.ai>
Date: Sat, 2 May 2026 11:06:49 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] input: register EM (666) and MIC (667) keycode labels for
 MP01
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Stock Minimal Phone MP01 firmware adds two non-AOSP keycodes for the
dedicated emoji and microphone hardware keys on the device's QWERTY
keyboard. The shipped Pastiera IME (vbbot/pastiera) checks keyCode ==
666 (KEYCODE_EM) and keyCode == 667 (KEYCODE_MIC) directly to open
its inline emoji picker and start speech-to-text respectively, with
no fallback / remapping for the standard EMOJI_PICKER (317) or
DICTATE (319) Android keycodes.

Add EM and MIC entries to KEYCODES_SEQUENCE so the .kl parser
(InputEventLookup::getKeyCodeByLabel) recognises them as valid
labels. The aw9523b-key.kl keylayout for the MP01 keyboard then
maps:

    key 250  EM      # emoji-key scancode (0xfa) → keycode 666
    key 251  MIC     # mic-key scancode (0xfb)   → keycode 667

The DEFINE_KEYCODE macro is bypassed for these entries because there
is no corresponding AKEYCODE_EM / AKEYCODE_MIC constant in
include/android/keycodes.h — we deliberately avoid touching the
public C header / KeyEvent.java since Pastiera uses the literal
values (not constant references) and no other code in our tree
references EM/MIC by name. Reverse lookup vec[666] / vec[667]
(getLabelByKeyCode, used only by debug logging) returns nullptr
because the value-indexed std::vector<InputEventLabel> ends at the
last sequential entry; the forward .kl-label-to-int unordered_map
lookup is what matters for keylayout parsing and works fine.

Change-Id: Ia93aa5d548cefbb52877e0f8794155398545e3fb
---
 libs/input/InputEventLabels.cpp | 13 ++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/libs/input/InputEventLabels.cpp b/libs/input/InputEventLabels.cpp
index b537feb68f..5d61401065 100644
--- a/libs/input/InputEventLabels.cpp
+++ b/libs/input/InputEventLabels.cpp
@@ -369,7 +369,18 @@ namespace android {
     DEFINE_KEYCODE(F21), \
     DEFINE_KEYCODE(F22), \
     DEFINE_KEYCODE(F23), \
-    DEFINE_KEYCODE(F24)
+    DEFINE_KEYCODE(F24), \
+    /* MP01: dedicated emoji + mic hardware keys. Stock MP01 firmware adds these
+       same numeric keycodes; the prebuilt Pastiera IME (vbbot/pastiera) checks
+       keyCode == 666 / 667 directly to open its emoji picker / start speech-to-text.
+       Bypass the DEFINE_KEYCODE macro since there is no AKEYCODE_EM / AKEYCODE_MIC
+       in the C header — we only need the .kl-label-to-int forward lookup, which
+       reads from the unordered_map<string,int>. The reverse vec[value] lookup
+       (debug logging only) returns nullptr for these high values, harmlessly.
+       Brace-init {label,value} matches both unordered_map<string,int> AND
+       vector<InputEventLabel> initializers (KEYCODES_SEQUENCE feeds both). */ \
+    {"EM", 666}, \
+    {"MIC", 667}
 
 // NOTE: If you add a new axis here you must also add it to several other files.
 //       Refer to frameworks/base/core/java/android/view/MotionEvent.java for the full list.
